        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p>Common questions about forex credit cards and international transactions</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            What is forex markup on credit cards?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Forex markup is an additional fee charged by credit card issuers on every international transaction. When you make a purchase in a foreign currency, the bank converts it to INR at the prevailing exchange rate and adds a markup fee — typically 2% to 3.5% — on top of that rate. This markup applies to both physical swipes abroad and online purchases from international merchants. Forex credit cards either eliminate this markup entirely (0%) or reduce it significantly, helping you save ₹200-₹350 per ₹10,000 spent internationally.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Which is the best zero forex markup credit card in India?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              The IDFC First WOW Credit Card is widely considered the best zero forex markup card in India as it offers 0% markup with no annual fee (lifetime free). For premium travellers, the Axis Atlas card offers 0% effective markup when you factor in the EDGE Miles earned on international spends. The Niyo Global card (SBM Bank) is another excellent option for students and budget travellers with zero markup and no joining fee. Your best choice depends on your spending volume and whether you value additional travel perks.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Can I use a forex credit card for online international purchases?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Absolutely. Forex credit cards work for both physical swipes abroad and online international purchases. Whether you're buying from Amazon US, paying for a Netflix international plan, subscribing to software services, or booking hotels on global travel sites, the zero forex markup benefit applies. Make sure your card is enabled for international transactions — you can usually toggle this in your banking app. Some cards may require you to set an international transaction limit for security purposes.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Do forex cards offer better exchange rates than money changers?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Generally, yes. Zero forex markup credit cards convert at the Visa or Mastercard interbank rate, which is typically 1-2% better than the rates offered by airport money changers or forex dealers. For example, if the interbank USD/INR rate is ₹83.50, a money changer might offer ₹85-₹86, while your zero markup card converts at ₹83.50. However, for large cash requirements abroad, consider carrying a prepaid forex card alongside your credit card, as some merchants and services may not accept cards.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Is there a limit on international transactions with forex cards?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Yes, there are limits governed by RBI's Liberalised Remittance Scheme (LRS). Indian residents can remit up to USD 250,000 per financial year for permissible transactions including travel, education, and overseas purchases. Within this limit, your individual transaction limit depends on your card's credit limit. Banks may set additional per-transaction or daily limits for security, which you can usually increase by contacting customer service or adjusting settings in your banking app. For education-related expenses, some banks offer enhanced limits with supporting documentation.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
